<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><iml:iml xmlns:iml="http://www.cs.unibo.it/2006/iml"><iml:head><iml:title>The irreducible complexity of the authorial chain in academic semantic publishing</iml:title><iml:meta name="author.1.number" content="1"/><iml:meta name="author.1.name" content="Silvio Peroni"/><iml:meta name="author.1.affiliation" content="University of Bologna@Italy"/><iml:meta name="author.1.email" content="speroni@cs.unibo.it"/><iml:meta name="author.2.number" content="2"/><iml:meta name="author.2.name" content="David Shotton"/><iml:meta name="author.2.affiliation" content="University of Oxford@UK"/><iml:meta name="author.2.email" content="david.shotton@zoo.ox.ac.uk"/><iml:meta name="author.3.number" content="3"/><iml:meta name="author.3.name" content="Fabio Vitali"/><iml:meta name="author.3.affiliation" content="University of Bologna@Italy"/><iml:meta name="author.3.email" content="fabio@cs.unibo.it"/></iml:head><iml:body><iml:div id="abs" class="abstract"><iml:h1>Abstract</iml:h1><iml:p>The semantic enhancement of a traditional scientific article is not a straightforward operation, even if we consider just the mere translation of the readable content in semantically precise statements. Still, there are more aspects involved, as the specification of the credibility level of the paper, the structural components of the paper, the argumentative model used, and finally the actual statement employed. In this paper we propose the <iml:i>semantical lenses</iml:i>, a model for the identification and the formal description of these different kinds of semantics, by introducing a number of ontologies and tools that help in both the description of the scientific article and in the use of the semantic annotations for subsequent purposes. </iml:p></iml:div><iml:div class="section"><iml:h1>Introduction</iml:h1><iml:p>The inception of the <iml:i>semantic publishing</iml:i> – i.e., the inclusion in a digitally-published scientific article of anything that enhances its meaning and enables its linking to semantically related articles or, more generally, resources <iml:a class="ref" href="ShottonSemanticPublishing"/> – is the current and consequential next-step of the digital publishing. The main reason of its success is the strategic and economic importance that the semantic publishing movement, and its network of semantically inter-linked resources, has for publishers: from reinforcing their public image of being always technologically up to date, to improving the quantity of readers from an article to its related webpage on the publisher website.</iml:p><iml:p>The enhancement of a traditional scientific article with semantic annotations is not a straightforward operation, even if we considered just the mere translation of the readable content into semantically precise statements. But, besides that, there are additional and subtle aspects involved:</iml:p><iml:ul type="bullet"><iml:li><iml:p>in order to provide the basis for the identification of the authoritativeness of the assertions, one needs to specify, at the global level, the full context in which the publishing activity takes place – affiliations of the authors, fundings that paid for the research, the peer review process it underwent, the impact factor of the journal, the acknowledgements of the authors, or, in short, anything that asserts and justifies the overall credibility context in which the scientific activity has taken place;</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li><iml:p>in order to provide the basis for the identification of the relative importance of each semantic assertion of the work, one needs to specify, at the paper level, the structural components, its fundamental elements and anything that improves or impacts on the clarity, readability and contextualization of the semantic assertions beyond and more than their actual meaning;</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li><iml:p>in order to show the rhetorical and argumentative organization of the assertions, one needs to specify, at a even lower level, the rhetorical devices used by the author that have an impact on the argumentation and persuasive power of the paper;</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li><iml:p>finally, to provide the actual statements that one needs to assert and that may correspond to individual sentences of the paper.</iml:p></iml:li></iml:ul><iml:p>Although all these different aspects live together simultaneously within an article, and are well integrated in the rhetorical flow of the natural language sentences that constitute a traditional scientific article, they can be actually defined and circumscribed in the semantic rendering of the paper by applying particular filters that enhance particular semantics, as if we were looking through <iml:i>semantic lenses</iml:i> that magnify some shapes and colours rather than others.</iml:p><iml:p>There are two operations associated to semantic lenses, of course: on the one hand, the <iml:i>application</iml:i> of a particular lens onto an article – i.e., the act of associating semantic data of that particular colour to the text – and, on the other hand, the <iml:i>focalisation</iml:i> of an article through a particular lens – i.e., the emersion of lens-related descriptive semantics previously associated to that article. </iml:p><iml:p>The application of a semantic lens represents an authorial activity <iml:i>per se</iml:i>, that results in a specific, potentially subjective, interpretation of the article according the scope of the lens. In fact, the agent that applies a lens holds a particular role that differs lens by lens and, even when two agents hold the same role because they applied the same lens, their interpretations – i.e., the set of statements they have expressed according to the particular lens scope – may differ because of different tools, skills and opinions that may affect and bias the writing and/or the conversion of the paper in a semantic form.</iml:p><iml:p>In this paper we propose a model for the semantic enhancement of documents based on seven different <iml:i>lenses</iml:i> that can be used to colour and semantically enhance scientific papers and we present a set of technologies (e.g., web tools, vocabularies and ontologies) that can be used for applying lenses to a document and for the specification of the authorial role held by each agent responsible for this operation.</iml:p><iml:p>The rest of the paper is structured as follows: in <iml:a class="ref" href="SectionSevenLenses"/> we introduce the lenses model, in <iml:a class="ref" href="SectionLensesOnArticle"/> we present all the tools and ontologies used to describe, in a proper format, each lens. In <iml:a class="ref" href="SectionRelatedWorks"/> we introduce previous and current works related to the topic, drawing some conclusion in <iml:a class="ref" href="SectionConclusions"/>.</iml:p></iml:div><iml:div id="SectionSevenLenses" class="section"><iml:h1>Describing document semantics through lenses</iml:h1><iml:p>The semantics of a scientific article (or, more generally, of a document) is investigable and definable at different perspectives. Each perspective is identifiable by a <iml:i>lens</iml:i> that can be <iml:i>applied</iml:i> to a document (for associating some semantic data to it) and then used to <iml:i>focalise</iml:i> the semantic assets previously associated. We identify seven different lenses that cover different semantic perspectives at different granularities, listed from coarsest to finest:</iml:p><iml:ul type="bullet"><iml:li><iml:p><iml:b>Context.</iml:b> The environment in which a paper is placed, in terms of involvement of research organizations, research members, research fundings, research process, research publication workflow, etc.</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li><iml:p><iml:b>Aggregation.</iml:b> How academic papers are grouped, e.g., in journals, and how references are grouped, e.g., in bibliographic collections, tables of content, reference lists, reference management systems and library catalogues.</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li><iml:p><iml:b>Structure.</iml:b> The organization of a scientific paper in sections, subsections, and its components such as paragraphs, tables, figures and formulas, the functional structures such as title, abstract, introduction, conclusion, references, acknowledgements.</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li><iml:p><iml:b>Rhetoric.</iml:b> The parts of the paper that carry specific scientific or academic meaning for the paper, which as introductory and conclusive texts, background, individual contributions, evaluations, method, etc. These parts may but do not necessarily correspond to a structural entity (e.g., a section) of the paper, and have usually no specific presentational characteristics.</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li><iml:p><iml:b>Citation.</iml:b> How academic papers and datasets are linked, with the formation of semantically rich citation networks.</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li><iml:p><iml:b>Argumentation.</iml:b> The organization of the argument of the paper, that is organized as a fractal representation of the same rhetorical devices that can be found at higher level (the whole paper considered as the report of an argumentation), as well as at the lowest level (each statement being the result of individual sub-arguments and counterarguments potentially expanding to the infinite).</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li><iml:p><iml:b>Semantics.</iml:b> The actual individual findings of the paper having scientific value and being expressible in some kind of formal knowledge representation.</iml:p></iml:li></iml:ul><iml:p>Since all these different kinds of semantics co-exist simultaneously within a document, the lenses are our mechanism for focussing or applying particular form of semantics rather than others. Moreover, the application of a lens intrinsically assigns a particular lens-related authorial role to the agent that performs the operation.</iml:p><iml:p>In the next sections we elaborate on these lenses, presenting tools and models for describing the application of each of them and for distinctly associating provenance information about their application.</iml:p></iml:div><iml:div id="SectionLensesOnArticle" class="section"><iml:h1>Lenses' road test</iml:h1><iml:p>The goal of this section is twofold: first, we elaborate on the theory behind the semantic lenses introduced in <iml:a class="ref" href="SectionSevenLenses"/> giving a more concrete description of them, and then we present tools, vocabularies and ontologies (developed either in previous works or specifically for this paper) that make possible the application of these lenses to documents by means of Semantic Web technologies.</iml:p><iml:div class="section"><iml:h1>The lens 'Context'</iml:h1><iml:p>Usually, writing an article is just one stage of a often complex and multi-domain activity that characterises the article itself in some way. Projects, organizations involved, people affiliated to these organizations, fundings: they are all contextual elements that take part, directly or not, to the genesis of the content of an article and that have a strong impact on the credibility and authoritativeness of the scientific findings of the paper.</iml:p><iml:p>Obviously, many vocabularies, models and ontologies were developed appositely for describing of these kinds of article-related contexts, such as <iml:i>Description Of A Project</iml:i><iml:a class="footnote" href="ftn4"/> (<iml:i>DOAP</iml:i>) for projects and <iml:i>Academic Research Project Funding Ontology</iml:i><iml:a class="footnote" href="ftn5"/> (<iml:i>ARPFO</iml:i>) for fundings. They can be easily used simultaneously for applying this particular lens on an article:</iml:p><iml:p class="code">:jisc projectfunding:provides [ 
  a projectfunding:Funding ;
  projectfunding:funds :open-citation-project ] .

:open-citation-project a projectfunding:Project ;
  dcterms:hasPart :spar ;
  projectfunding:hasPrincipalInvestigator :david-shotton .

:spar a projectfunding:ProjectSection , doap:Project ;
  doap:homepage &lt;http://purl.org/spar&gt; ;
  doap:maintainer :david-shotton , :silvio-peroni
  foaf:page &lt;http://www.essepuntato.it/tpdl2011/paper&gt; .

&lt;http://www.essepuntato.it/tpdl2011/paper&gt; #this article
  dcterms:creator :silvio-peroni , :david-shotton , :fabio-vitali .

:david-shotton a foaf:Person ; foaf:name “David Shotton” .
:silvio-peroni a foaf:Person ; foaf:name “Silvio Peroni” .
:fabio-vitali a foaf:Person ; foaf:name “Fabio Vitali” .</iml:p></iml:div><iml:div class="section"><iml:h1>The lens 'Aggregation'</iml:h1><iml:p>Going further in the social context in which a document is initially thought and written, it is also significative to understand in which way documents are grouped together. For instance, considering academic papers, it is relevant to understand in which books and/or journals they were included and how their references were grouped (e.g., in tables of contents, reference lists, reference management systems, library catalogues, etc.).</iml:p><iml:p>For applying this lens, we need vocabularies that allow us to describe both document containers (journals, conference proceedings, book series, and other kinds of documents and document collections) and sets of related references about documents. From the gathering of models developed for document descriptions, we propose to use the <iml:i>FRBR-aligned Bibliographic Ontology</iml:i> (<iml:i>FaBiO</iml:i>)<iml:a class="footnote" href="ftn6"/> and the <iml:i>Bibliographic Reference Ontology</iml:i> (<iml:i>BiRO</iml:i>)<iml:a class="footnote" href="ftn7"/> for the application of this lens to documents, since they have been developed exactly to describe the aforementioned concepts:</iml:p><iml:p class="code">&lt;http://www.essepuntato.it/tpdl2011/paper&gt; a fabio:ConferencePaper
  ; frbr:part [ a biro:BibliographicList 
    ; c:firstItem [ c:itemContent [ biro:references &lt;http://dx.doi.org/10.1145/585058.585081&gt; ] ]
    ; c:nextItem [ c:itemContent [ biro:references &lt;http://www.ploscompbiol.org/doi/pcbi.1000361&gt; ] ] ] ] .

&lt;http://www.ploscompbiol.org/doi/pcbi.1000361&gt; a fabio:JournalArticle
  ; frbr:partOf [ a fabio:JournalIssue ; prism:issueIdentifier “4”
  ; frbr:partOf [ a fabio:JournalVolume ; prism:volume “5”
  ; frbr:partOf [ a fabio:Journal 
    ; dc:title “PloS Computational Biology” ] ] ] . …</iml:p></iml:div><iml:div id="SectionStructure" class="section"><iml:h1>The lens 'Structure'</iml:h1><iml:p>The structure of a textual document is often expressed by means of markup languages, such as XML and LaTeX, that have constructs for organizing, even hierarchically, its textual content. XML is the most used end-format for expressing syntactic structures on text but it has two main problems for our purposes: </iml:p><iml:ul type="bullet"><iml:li><iml:p>it does not allow to specify in a formal way any kind of <iml:i>markup semantics</iml:i><iml:a class="footnote" href="ftn0"/> – a markup item <iml:span class="code">&lt;p&gt;</iml:span> is just an XML element having the string “p” as name, but what that element really <iml:i>means</iml:i> (e.g., what a paragraph actually <iml:i>is</iml:i>) is not directly expressible through XML;</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li><iml:p>there is no standard way to express any additional semantics upon a range of text components without modifying the structure of an article; although RDFa <iml:a class="ref" href="RDFa"/> may be considered a reasonable candidate, it always obliges to add new structural elements around text, such as <iml:span class="code">&lt;span&gt;</iml:span>s, that change the structural nature of the document.</iml:p></iml:li></iml:ul><iml:p>To avoid those issues, we can use EARMARK <iml:a class="ref" href="EARMARKEKAW"/>, an ontology<iml:a class="footnote" href="ftn9"/> (summarized in <iml:a class="ref" href="FigureEARMARK"/>) that can describe the syntactical nature of markup items, including their containment relations, and defining, in practice, a meta-markup language more expressive than XML and expressed in a format suitable for adding semantics through RDF. Moreover, in order to help end-user to use this technology, we developed a tool for converting XML documents into EARMARK (linearised in RDF/XML)<iml:a class="footnote" href="ftn10"/> and an API to create and modify EARMARK documents within Java-based applications<iml:a class="footnote" href="ftn11"/>.</iml:p><iml:div id="FigureEARMARK" class="picture"><iml:p class="img.block"><iml:img class="17cm-12.749cm" src="10000201000003200000025853BBE5A8.png"/></iml:p><iml:p class="caption">A graphical representation of the EARMARK ontology.</iml:p></iml:div><iml:p>EARMARK documents are expressed through ontologies that specify statements that describe the textual content and structure of the document. It is also possible to associate a particular structural semantics (e.g., that an element <iml:span class="code">&lt;p&gt;</iml:span> <iml:i>expresses</iml:i> the concept of paragraph) by using an accompanying ontology that describes the various components of a document, such as the <iml:i>Document Components Ontology</iml:i> (<iml:i>DoCO</iml:i>)<iml:a class="footnote" href="ftn12"/>. For instance, the first section of this paper can be described as follows:</iml:p><iml:p class="code">&lt;http://www.essepuntato.it/tpdl2011/paper&gt; a owl:Ontology .

:div1 a earmark:Element ; la:expresses doco:Section
  ; earmark:hasGeneralIdentifier “div”
  ; earmark:hasNamespace “http://www.cs.unibo.it/2006/iml”
  ; c:firstItem [ c:itemContent :h1
  ; c:nextItem [ c:itemContent :p1
  ; c:nextItem [ … ] ] ] .

:h1 a earmark:Element ; la:expresses doco:SectionTitle
  ; earmark:hasGeneralIdentifier “h1”
  ; earmark:hasNamespace “http://www.cs.unibo.it/2006/iml” 
  ; c:firstItem [ c:itemContent :r1 ] .

:p1 a earmark:Element ; la:expresses doco:Paragraph
  ; earmark:hasGeneralIdentifier “p” …

:r1 a earmark:PointerRange ; earmark:refersTo :docuverse
  ; earmark:begins “0” ; earmark:ends “12” .

:docuverse a earmark:StringDocuverse #it contains the textual content of the document
  ; earmark:hasContent “Introduction The …” . … </iml:p></iml:div><iml:div class="section"><iml:h1>The lens 'Rhetoric'</iml:h1><iml:p>Often, scientific journals impose to their articles to follow a particular rhetoric segmentation, in order to explicitly identify meaningful parts of an article from a scientific point of view, such as <iml:i>introduction</iml:i>, <iml:i>background</iml:i>, <iml:i>evaluation</iml:i>, <iml:i>materials</iml:i>, <iml:i>methods</iml:i>, <iml:i>conclusion</iml:i>, etc. Although these parts usually (but do not necessarily) correspond to structural entities of the article, such as sections, they carry a specific semantics that characterises all the text they contain more than being simply <iml:i>within a section</iml:i>.</iml:p><iml:p>In previous works, models have been created for describing the rhetoric aspect of a scientific publication: all the rhetorical blocks in the <iml:i>Semantical Annotated LaTeX</iml:i> (SALT) <iml:a class="ref" href="GrozaSalt"/> and the <iml:i>Ontology of Rhetorical Blocks</iml:i> (<iml:i>ORB</iml:i>) <iml:a class="ref" href="CiccareseORB"/> are all relevant examples, as well as <iml:i>Discourse Elements Ontology</iml:i> (<iml:i>DEO</iml:i>)<iml:a class="footnote" href="ftn14"/>:</iml:p><iml:p class="code">:div1 la:expresses deo:Introduction .
:div2 la:expresses deo:Model . …</iml:p></iml:div><iml:div class="section"><iml:h1>The lens 'Citation'</iml:h1><iml:p>Understanding and describing how articles cite each others is important for calculating indexes to measure the productivity and the impact of scientists and journals. Though the citation network used for that purpose is usually calculated considering which and how much an article is cited by the citing ones, it is important not to lose sight of the rhetorical reasons of a citation, that may affect significantly the measurements on the network. In fact, it seems plausible to consider differently the weight of a citation that aims at criticising or disagreeing with the cited work and the weight of those citations used for confirming or extending the work of a cited article.</iml:p><iml:p>The <iml:i>Citation Typing Ontology</iml:i> (<iml:i>CiTO</iml:i>)<iml:a class="footnote" href="ftn15"/> allows to define all this kinds of citations, both <iml:i>factual</iml:i> and <iml:i>rhetorical</iml:i>, in order to characterise properly the nature of a citation:</iml:p><iml:p class="code">&lt;http://www.essepuntato.it/tpdl2011/paper&gt; 
  cito:citesForInformation 
    &lt;http://www.ploscompbiol.org/doi/pcbi.1000361&gt; ,
    &lt;http://dx.doi.org/10.1145/585058.585081&gt; ;
  cito:usesMethodIn &lt;http://isbn.nu/978-0521092302&gt; .</iml:p></iml:div><iml:div class="section"><iml:h1>The lens 'Argumentation'</iml:h1><iml:p>In his fundamental work <iml:a class="ref" href="ToulminUsesOfArgument"/>, Toulmin explains that each argument (including scientific arguments) is composed of statements each belonging to one of the following six roles:</iml:p><iml:ul type="bullet"><iml:li><iml:p><iml:b>Claim.</iml:b> A fact that must be established – “This is a scientific article”.</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li><iml:p><iml:b>Evidence.</iml:b> Another fact that represents a foundation for the claim – “This article has been submitted to a scientific conference”.</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li><iml:p><iml:b>Warrant.</iml:b> A statement bridging from the evidence to the claim – “An article submitted to a scientific conference is a scientific article.”.</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li><iml:p><iml:b>Backing (optional).</iml:b> Sort of credentials that certifies the warrant – the Call for Papers of the International Conference on Theory and Practice of Digital Libraries 2011.</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li><iml:p><iml:b>Rebuttal (optional).</iml:b> Restrictions that may be applied to the claim – “Unless conference reviewers will reject it, considering it non-scientific at all”.</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li><iml:p><iml:b>Qualifier (optional).</iml:b> It expresses the degree of certainty concerning the claim via words or phrases such as “certainly”, “possible”, “probably” – “presumably” for our example.</iml:p></iml:li></iml:ul><iml:p>Toulmin's argumentation model is organized as a <iml:i>fractal</iml:i>: each instance that has a certain role in an argumentation (e.g., a warrant) may very well be the claim of another sub-argumentation explicitly present in the paper, and recursively each statement of the sub-argumentation could have been, in turn, the claim of other sub-sub-argumentations, etc.</iml:p><iml:p>In order to use this argumentation theory, we developed the <iml:i>Argument Model Ontology</iml:i> (<iml:i>AMO</iml:i>)<iml:a class="footnote" href="ftn16"/>, an OWL ontology that allows to express the Toulmin's model for argumentation, as shown in the following excerpt:</iml:p><iml:p class="code">:sentence1 rdfs:label “This is a scientific article” .
:sentence2 rdfs:label “This article has been submitted to a scientific conference” .
:sentence3 rdfs:label “An article submitted to a scientific conference is a scientific article” .

:argument1 a amo:Argument ; amo:hasClaim :sentence1
  ; amo:hasEvidence :sentence2 ; amo:hasWarrant :sentence3 .

:argument2 a amo:Argument ; amo:hasClaim :sentence3 … </iml:p></iml:div><iml:div class="section"><iml:h1>The lens 'Semantics'</iml:h1><iml:p>The main goal of a scientific article is to indicate (and cite) findings having a specific scientific value. Usually, these finding are expressed through text content, tables, figures used as static information devices, that can be interpretable by humans only and, of course, are not directly suitable for machines. This because the semantics of a piece of text, such as “EARMARK is more expressive than XML”, is not explicitly defined in a formal way: it is just text.</iml:p><iml:p>Adding within an article formal semantic statements intrinsically asserted by the article itself, by means of its textual content, it is possible using Semantic Web technologies such as RDF:</iml:p><iml:p class="code">&lt;http://www.essepuntato.it/2008/12/earmark&gt; 
  :isMoreExpressiveThan &lt;http://www.w3.org/XML&gt; .</iml:p></iml:div></iml:div><iml:div class="section"><iml:h1>Lens application is authorial operation</iml:h1><iml:p>The application of a particular lens to an article by adding information about the semantics described by the lens, is an <iml:i>authorial operation</iml:i>, i.e., an act involving agents as responsible for the specification of certain semantic interpretations of a document. Tracking lens applications is a typical problem of <iml:i>data provenance</iml:i>, i.e., the identification of processes and agents controlling them involved in the creation of an artefact or resource.</iml:p><iml:p>Many vocabularies were developed for expressing provenance information through Semantic Web Technologies. In our opinion, the <iml:i>Open Provenance Model Vocabulary</iml:i> (<iml:i>OPMV</iml:i>) <iml:a class="ref" href="JunOPMV"/> is one of the more appropriate vocabularies for the definition of the authorial role of agents responsible for lens application. Accordingly to the suggestion of the guidelines of that vocabulary<iml:a class="footnote" href="ftn17"/>, each set of RDF statements, produced as consequence of a lens application, should be enclosed within a <iml:i>named graph</iml:i> <iml:a class="ref" href="CarrollNamedGraphs"/>, in order to express all the provenance data as statements about the graph itself:</iml:p><iml:p class="code">:structure-lens {
  &lt;http://www.essepuntato.it/tpdl2011/paper&gt; a owl:Ontology .

  :div1 a earmark:Element ; la:expresses doco:Section
    ; earmark:hasGeneralIdentifier “div” … }

:structure-lens a opmv:Artifact , lens:StructureLensApplication
  ; xslt:wasResultOf [ a xslt:Transformation 
    ; xslt:source &lt;http://www.essepuntato.it/tpdl2011/paper/xml&gt; 
    ; xslt:stylesheet &lt;http://www.essepuntato.it/xml2earmark/xslt&gt; 
    ; opmv:isPerformedBy &lt;http://www.essepuntato.it/xml2earmark&gt; ] .

:citation-lens {
  &lt;http://www.essepuntato.it/tpdl2011/paper&gt; 
    cito:citesForInformation 
      &lt;http://www.ploscompbiol.org/doi/pcbi.1000361&gt; , … }

:citation-lens a opmv:Artifact , lens:CitationLensApplication
  ; opmv:wasGeneratedBy [ a opmv:Process
    ; opmv:isPerformedBy &lt;http://www.essepuntato.it/about/me&gt; ] . …</iml:p></iml:div><iml:div id="SectionRelatedWorks" class="section"><iml:h1>Related works</iml:h1><iml:p>There exists a lot of literature that concerns models for semantically describing digital publishing from different points of view. Because of this richness, here we present just some of the most important and significant works on this topic.</iml:p><iml:p>One of the most famous ontology for describing bibliographic entities and their aggregating aspects is the <iml:i>Bibliographic Ontology</iml:i> (<iml:i>BIBO</iml:i>) <iml:a class="ref" href="Bibo"/>, a model originally created to be used either for citations, for classifying documents or, more simply, for describing any kind of document in RDF. The <iml:i>Functional Requirements for Bibliographic Records</iml:i> (<iml:i>FRBR</iml:i>) <iml:a class="ref" href="FRBR"/> is yet another, much more structured, model for describing documents and their evolution in time. One of the most important aspects of FRBR is the fact that it is not tied up with a particular metadata schema or implementation. It is implemented as RDF vocabulary and as OWL 2 DL ontology<iml:a class="footnote" href="ftn19"/>.</iml:p><iml:p>The <iml:i>RDF Textual Encoding Framework</iml:i> (<iml:i>RDFTef</iml:i>) <iml:a class="ref" href="TummarelloRDFTef"/> is an open-source API that allows to mark documents up by means of Semantic Web technologies. This API was created to demonstrate a plausible way for handling overlapping markup within documents, identifying textual content of a document as a set of independent RDF resources that can be linked mutually and with other parent (e.g., container) resources. Beside adding the possibility of defining more than one structural markup hierarchy on the same text content, using RDF as language for encoding markup allows to specify semantic data on textual content as well.</iml:p><iml:p>From a rhetoric perspective, the <iml:i>Ontology of Rhetorical Blocks</iml:i> (<iml:i>ORB</iml:i>) <iml:a class="ref" href="CiccareseORB"/>, the <iml:i>SALT </iml:i><iml:i>Rhetoric Ontology</iml:i> <iml:a class="ref" href="GrozaSalt"/> and the <iml:i>Medium-Grained structure</iml:i> <iml:a class="ref" href="DeWaardDocumentStructure"/> offer, the formers, a coarse-grained (header, introduction, methods) and, the latter, a medium-grained description (hypothesis, objects of study, direct representation of measurements) of the rhetorical components of a document.</iml:p><iml:p>Moreover, SALT <iml:a class="ref" href="GrozaClaim"/> also permits an agent, such as the author of the scientific publication himself/herself, “to enrich the document with formal descriptions of claims, supports and rhetorical relation as part of their writing process”. About this topic, there are other works, based on the Toulmin model <iml:a class="ref" href="ToulminUsesOfArgument"/>, that offer an application of this argumentation technique within other domains, such as legal and legislative domains <iml:a class="ref" href="LauritsenDocumentModeling"/>.</iml:p><iml:p>Speaking about authorial roles and provenance, the <iml:i>Open Provenance Model</iml:i> (<iml:i>OPM</iml:i>) <iml:a class="ref" href="MoreauOpenProvenanceModel"/>, and the related RDF vocabulary <iml:a class="ref" href="JunOPMV"/>, is a well-known model for provenance, whose main requirements concerns the exchangeability of provenance data between systems, the digital representation of provenance for any resource and the definition of a set of rules identifying which are the valid inferences that can be made on provenance graphs. Another implemented model for provenance is included in the SWAN ontology ecosystem <iml:a class="ref" href="CiccareseSWAN"/>, and aims to describes resources in terms of their accessing, authoring and versioning.</iml:p></iml:div><iml:div id="SectionConclusions" class="section"><iml:h1>Conclusion</iml:h1><iml:p>In this paper we introduced a model for the semantic enhancement of documents based on seven different <iml:i>lenses</iml:i>, each of them able to identify a specific semantical point of view of a document. Moreover, we present a set of technologies (e.g., web tools, vocabularies and ontologies) that can be used for applying lenses to a document and for the specification of the authorial role held by the agent responsible for this operation.</iml:p><iml:p>Future works will concern mainly the improvement of the models used for lens applications, the development of automatic and semi-automatic tools for the application of these lenses to documents, and the implementation of user interfaces for a dynamic focalisation of lens-related document semantics.</iml:p></iml:div><iml:div id="references" class="bibliography"><iml:h1>References</iml:h1><iml:ul type="bullet"><iml:li id="ShottonSemanticPublishing"><iml:p>Shotton, D., Portwin, K., Klyne, G., Miles, A. (2009). Adventures in Semantic Publishing: Exemplar Semantic Enhancements of a Research Article. PLoS Comput Biol 5(4): e1000361. doi:10.1371/journal.pcbi.1000361</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li id="ToulminUsesOfArgument"><iml:p>Toulmin, S. (1959). The uses of argument. Cambridge University Press.</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li id="GrozaSalt"><iml:p>Groza, T., Handschuh, S., Möller, K., Decker, S. (2007). SALT – Semantically Annotated LaTeX for Scientific Publications. In Proceedings of the 4th European Semantic Web Conference (ESWC 2007). Innsbruck, Austria.</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li id="GrozaClaim"><iml:p>Groza, T., Möller, K., Handschuh, S., Trif, D., Decker, S. (2007). SALT: Weaving the claim web. In Proceedings of the 6th International Semantic Web Conference (ISWC 2007). Boston, MA, USA.</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li id="RenearTowardsSemantics"><iml:p>Renear, A., Dubin, D., Sperberg-McQueen, C. M. (2002). Towards a Semantics for XML Markup. In the Proceedings of the 2002 ACM Symposium on Document Engineering. McLean, Virginia.</iml:p></iml:li><iml:li id="CiccareseORB"><iml:p>Cicc